[2] Suspected, funding
11 Nov 2015 Brazil: Brazilian man being tested for Ebola; results in 24 hours
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2015-11-brazilian-ebola-results-hours.html
[According to Brazil's health minister who spoke yesterday, (10 Nov 2015), a 46-year-old Brazilian man is being transferred to Brazil's top infectious disease hospital in Rio de Janeiro where he will undergo tests, including testing for Ebola virus disease (EVD). The man recently traveled to West Guinea and returned to Brazil on 6 Nov 2015. He went to a clinic 2 days later with symptoms including a high fever. Health workers who came in contact with him are being monitored.]

10 Nov 2015 Guinea: Ebola lingers in Guinea, where outbreak began
http://www.voanews.com/content/ebola-lingers-in-guinea-where-outbreak-began/3052246.html
[Guinea, where the Ebola virus disease (EVD) 1st occurred almost 2 years ago, is the last country in West Africa with an active outbreak. Part of the reason for the continued outbreak is resistance from the community over the necessary steps to be taken to both treat EVD and bring the outbreak to an end. The steps at issue include refusal to follow preventative measures to stop EVD transmission, with many residents preferring to follow the treatments and advice of traditional healers.]

10 Nov 2015 Liberia: Monrovia mayor led life and death battle against Ebola
http://allafrica.com/stories/201511110821.html
[The mayor of Paynesville, Cyvette Gibson, dealt with the Ebola virus disease (EVD) at the height of the outbreak by organizing more than 300 block leaders around 30 community builders in the red-light district of the city, a commercial district, to educate the population of 400 000, monitor their behavior, and trace potential EVD victims before they could spread the disease. Her efforts, backed by the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), was successful in reducing the number of Ebola cases in the neighborhood to zero. These results emphasize the role played by women and women's groups, and reinforce the reality that few people in society can mobilize communities as effectively as women.]

9 Nov 2015 UK: 10 staff exposed to Ebola at Glasgow's Queen Elizabeth University Hospital after sample blunder
http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/health/ten-staff-exposed-ebola-glasgows-6801300
[On 8 Nov 2015, a whistle-blowing scientist at Queen Elizabeth University Hospital (QEUH) said hard-pressed staff did not label an Ebolavirus sample as high risk. As a result, 10 hospital staff require check-ups to make sure they were not infected.

According to the unnamed scientist: "We had an Ebola crisis where a doctor who had seen the patient took a sample to the lab but didn't label it as high risk. About 10 people had to take their temperatures 3 times a day for weeks and phone them in to make sure they didn't have Ebola. ...They wouldn't let them travel on public transport, but they were allowed to come into work and risk infecting their colleagues."]

10 Nov 2015 USA (NY): Brooklyn inmate under Ebola quarantine released to the Feds
http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn-inmate-ebola-quarantine-released-feds-article-1.2430329
[A Brooklyn inmate under Ebola quarantine at the Metropolitan Detention Center since he arrived on a flight from Sierra Leone has been released to the custody of federal agents. The man, WT, was arrested in October 2015 by US Marshals at the John F. Kennedy International Airport and placed under isolation for 21 days, without the presence of symptoms. According to federal agents' statement to Judge Frederic Block, [the inmate] was placed in solitary confinement as a protection from other inmates who might erroneously believe he was infected with the Ebola virus disease (EVD). Judge Block refused a request for release on bail. Instead, the inmate was transported Kansas (USA) where he was indicted on unrelated charges from 2013.]

7 Nov 2015 Regional: West African governments must integrate trained Ebola responders into community-based health systems
http://allafrica.com/stories/201511091651.html
[According to the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC), all West African countries affected by the Ebola virus disease (EVD) epidemic should integrate trained responders into their community-based health systems.]

Funding
-----
10 Nov 2015 Liberia: World Bank project targets Ebola-affected households
http://allafrica.com/stories/201511101011.html
[The World Bank Board of Executive Directors today (10 Nov 2015) approved a new USD 10 million International Development Association (IDA) credit for the Liberian government to improve access to income generation opportunities for targeted youth and to support strengthening the government's ability to implement its cash transfer program.]

